    'PASSENGER_S03_TECH_001' => [
        'briefing_json' => [
            'en' => [
                'situation'           => 'You are Master of a 4,500-passenger cruise ship at sea in the Eastern Mediterranean. It is 02:30 and the fire detection system has activated alarms in Zone 7 — Deck 9 midship passenger cabin corridor containing 120 cabins with approximately 250 passengers sleeping. The fire panel shows three smoke detectors activated in sequence along the corridor (detectors 7-042, 7-044, 7-046 — spaced 12 metres apart) over a 90-second period, suggesting smoke migration along the corridor rather than a single detector fault. However, this same zone has experienced six false alarms in the previous 72 hours, all attributed to HVAC duct condensation following a return air duct insulation replacement completed two days ago by the HVAC team. The Chief Engineer has been called and advises: "99% certain it is another false alarm — same detectors, same sequential pattern as the previous six incidents, we are still getting condensation drip onto the detector heads from the new insulation." However, information has just reached the bridge that was not previously available: a passenger cabin steward conducting their routine rounds on Deck 9 reported smelling "something electrical — like hot wiring" near cabin 9147 approximately 15 minutes ago. This report was made to the housekeeping supervisor and did not reach the bridge until now due to a communication breakdown. Cabin 9147 is located between detectors 7-044 and 7-046. The fire patrol team has been dispatched with a thermal imaging camera — they report normal temperatures at the three detector heads consistent with condensation, BUT cabin 9147\'s door is warm to the touch and they can detect a faint haze at the base of the door when viewed with a flashlight from a low angle. The fire team of six trained firefighters is on standby at the fire station in full BA gear. The Safety Officer is recommending immediate evacuation of Zone 7 (250 sleeping passengers), but the Hotel Director warns that evacuating elderly passengers (average age 68 on this Mediterranean itinerary) through narrow corridors at 02:30 with emergency alarms sounding risks falls, cardiac events, and crowd crush injuries — he cites a 2019 incident on another vessel where a false alarm evacuation resulted in 12 passenger injuries.',
